Human: Can you explain how potential energy works?

Assistant: Of course. Potential energy is the “stored energy” in something. If you lift up a rock, that takes effort. You expend energy, and it takes energy to move. But if you stand it on a table or put it back on the ground, it’s no longer doing any work. At this point, the rock is doing no work. The work done in lifting up the rock is called “potential energy.” When you stop lifting the rock, the potential energy becomes a “stored energy” — i.e. the rock is just there on the table, and does no work.  If you push the rock onto the table, that adds “kinetic energy,” but if you just rest it on the table, it becomes “potential energy.”

Assistant: Kanji is the set of characters in the Japanese language that is based on Chinese characters and ideograms. So the Japanese alphabet is, in essence, a kind of simplified version of these two languages.  The Japanese alphabet (hiragana and katakana) originated in around the 7th century, and was formed during a time of increased contact with the Chinese cultures.  However, in the same way that English uses its own alphabet, along with Latin letters and some Greek letters, Japanese didn’t adopt the Greek alphabet.  This means the Japanese alphabet doesn’t include any letters with straight lines or curves (also called “letters of the AB system”) -- only the Greek / Roman sounds.
